  "original_title": "\u0db8\u0db1\u0dca\u0d9a\u0dd2\u0db4\u0ddc\u0d9a\u0dca\u0dc3\u0dca \u0dbb\u0ddd\u0d9c\u0dd3\u0db1\u0dca\u0d9c\u0dda \u0db4\u0dc4\u0dc5 \u0dc0\u0dd0\u0da7\u0dd3\u0db8\u0d9a\u0dca - WHO",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "A drop in monkeypox cases - WHO",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "The number of monkeypox cases reported globally has fallen by 21% in the past week, signaling that a month-long trend of rising infections may be reversing and the outbreak in Europe may be starting to decline, the World Health Organization (WHO) said.",
        "The United Nations health agency reported 5,907 new cases weekly, with Iran and Indonesia reporting their first cases. Since the end of April, more than 45,000 cases of monkeypox have been reported in 98 countries.",
        "In the past month, 60% of the cases were reported from America, while Europe accounts for 38%, according to the World Health Organization. It said infections in the US showed a \"steady rise\".",
        "At a press conference on Thursday, WHO Director-General Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus said that while there were signs that Europe's monkeypox epidemic, which once accounted for 90% of the world's laboratory-confirmed cases, was slowing, the spread of the virus was now causing concern in other regions."
      ],
